    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>What makes a stock volatile?</summary>
        <p>A stock is volatile if its price fluctuates rapidly and significantly in a short period. This can be driven by low liquidity, speculative trading, or high sensitivity to news.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What types of stocks are usually the most volatile?</summary>
        <p>Penny stocks, early-stage biotech companies, small-cap tech startups, and meme stocks are typically among the most volatile.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>How is volatility measured?</summary>
        <p>Volatility is commonly measured using 'Beta'. A Beta greater than 1.0 indicates that the stock is more volatile than the broader market.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Can you make money on volatile stocks?</summary>
        <p>Yes, high volatility creates opportunities for large short-term gains, which is why day traders often seek them out. However, the risk of massive losses is equally high.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Should beginners invest in highly volatile stocks?</summary>
        <p>It is generally recommended that beginners avoid highly volatile stocks or limit them to a very small percentage of their portfolio due to the extreme risk.</p>
